Tuesday marks <a  style="color:#000000;font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;margin:0 !important;padding:0 !important;line-height:100% !important;mso-line-height-rule:exactly !important;" href="https://click.pulse.celebrations.com/?qs=c6cef39bff559a9b53ef7ea106536115439b7218d547ea755c70258af7cb8e18ca1b4e8095a61adf5bf0a33233ca42ac754a94d71e03b3f87779867a952c06eb">Veterans Day</a>, which was established to honor peace and those who fought to secure it in World War I. Over time, it’s grown into a day to recognize every man and woman who has worn our nation’s uniform and the families who’ve stood beside them.
    <br><br>
Each year, I try to pause on 11/11 to remember the people behind the service. A simple “thank you” goes a long way, but sometimes the most meaningful gesture is to ask a veteran about their experience — what they saw, what they learned, and how it shaped their life.
